🔴 Deutsche Zeitformen (Zamanlar)
          Präsens (Şimdiki/Geniş Zaman)
          Perfekt  (Geçmiş - Konuşma dili) --> sein und haben
          Präteritum (Geçmiş - Yazılı/Resmi dil) --> A1 seviyesinde sadece 2 tane fiili öğren yeterli
          Konjunktiv 2 (Kapsamlı bir konu ama A1de Sadece Rica formu öğretilir. B1-B2 halen devam edersin)
          Futur 1 (Gelecek Zaman)

        Präsens                 (Present/Present Continuous/Future tense): 
                                Used to describe actions or events that are happening now or habitual actions.
                                        Ich spiele Tennis." (I am playing tennis.)

        Präteritum              (Simple past tense): 
                                Generally used in written language and formal speech to describe completed actions in the past.
                                        "Ich spielte Tennis." (I played tennis.)
        Imperfekt               (Imperfect tense):
                                Similar to the simple past tense, it is used to describe actions in the past, but more commonly used in spoken language.
                                        "Ich spielte Tennis." (I played tennis.)

        Perfekt                 (Present perfect tense): 
                                Used to talk about completed actions in the past with a connection to the present.
                                        "Ich habe Tennis gespielt." (I have played tennis.)

        Plusquamperfekt         (Past perfect tense): 
                                Used to express actions that happened before another event in the past.
                                        "Ich hatte Tennis gespielt, als es zu regnen begann." (I had played tennis when it started to rain.)

        Futur I                 (Future tense): 
                                Used to express actions that will happen in the future.
                                        "Ich werde Tennis spielen." (I will play tennis.)

        - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -

        Präsensprogressiv       (Present progressive): 
                                This is a compound tense used to express actions that are happening at the moment of speaking.
                                        "Ich bin am Tennis spielen." (I am playing tennis.)

        Futur II                (Future II):
                                A compound tense used to express actions that will be completed in the future before another event takes place.
                                        "Ich werde Tennis gespielt haben, wenn du kommst."         (I will have played tennis by the time you come.)

        Konditional I           (Conditional I): 
                                A compound tense used to express hypothetical situations or polite requests.
                                        "Ich würde Tennis spielen." (I would play tennis.)

        Konditional II          (Conditional II): 
                                A compound tense used to express unreal or hypothetical situations in the past.
                                        "Ich würde Tennis gespielt haben, wenn es nicht geregnet hätte." (I would have played tennis if it hadn't rained.)

        Perfektprogressiv       (Present perfect progressive): 
                                A compound tense used to express ongoing actions that started in the past and are still continuing in the present.
                                        "Ich bin seit einer Stunde am Tennis spielen." (I have been playing tennis for an hour.)



- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 
🔴 Konjunktiv (subjunctive mood)
        to express uncertainty, wishes, possibilities, politeness, or hypothetical situations. There are two main forms of the Konjunktiv: Konjunktiv I and Konjunktiv II.

        Konjunktiv I:
        Konjunktiv I is often used in indirect speech, reported speech, and to express impersonal statements. It is also used in written language, especially in more formal contexts.
        Example (reported speech):
                Direct speech: "Ich gehe ins Kino." (I am going to the cinema.)
                Indirect speech (Konjunktiv I): Er sagte, er gehe ins Kino. (He said he was going to the cinema.)

        Example (impersonal statement):
                "Es sei denn, du kommst rechtzeitig." (Unless you come on time.)

        Konjunktiv II:
        Konjunktiv II is used to express unreal or hypothetical situations, wishes, doubts, or polite requests. It is commonly used in both written and spoken language.
        Example (unreal situation):
                "Wenn ich mehr Zeit hätte, würde ich mehr lesen." (If I had more time, I would read more.)

        Example (wish):
                "Ich wünschte, ich wäre schon im Urlaub." (I wish I were already on vacation.)

        Example (polite request):
                "Könnten Sie mir bitte helfen?" (Could you please help me?)


        Both forms of Konjunktiv are conjugated similarly, 
        but Konjunktiv I is more regular and can often be formed by modifying the stem of the infinitive, while Konjunktiv II can have irregular forms. 
        The choice between Konjunktiv I and Konjunktiv II depends on the context and the verb being used.

        It's important to note that the use of Konjunktiv has become less common in colloquial German and is more prevalent in formal writing, legal texts, and some journalistic styles. 
        However, it is still an essential aspect of German grammar, and learners should be familiar with its usage.



